1834|publisher=Stamperia della Rev. Camera Apostolica|location=Roma|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ferranti|first=Giuseppe Manini|title=Compendio della storia sacra e politica di Ferrara|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bM0OAAAAQAAJ|volume=Tomo II|year=1808|publisher=Socj Bianci e Negri|location=Ferrara|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ferranti|first=Giuseppe Manini|title=Compendio della Storia sacra e politica di Ferrara|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1OxgdJuQLLcC&pg=RA1-PA193|volume=Tomo III|year=1808b|publisher=Bianchi e Negri|location=Ferrara|language=Italian|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|last=Fontanini |first=Giusto|title=Il dominio temporale della sede apostolica sopra la citta di Comacchio|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_U10leLeKg2wC|year=1709|location=Roma|language=Italian}}\n*Kehr, Paul Fridolin (1906). ''Italia Pontificia'' [https://archive.org/details/italiapontificia05cath Vol. V: Aemilia, sive Provincia Ravennas]. Berlin: Weidmann. (in Latin).\n* Lanzoni, Francesco (1898). [https://archive.org/stream/3attiememoriedepu27depuuoft#page/62/mode/2up ''Il primo vescovo di Comacchio''], in Atti e memorie della regia deputazione di storia patria per le Provincie di Romagna, Terza serie, vol. XXVII, 1909, pp.&nbsp;62\u201370\n* Lanzoni, Francesco (1927). ''[https://archive.org/stream/MN5017ucmf_0#page/n860/mode/2up Le diocesi d'Italia dalle origini al principio del secolo VII (an. 604)]'', vol. II, Faenza 1927, p.&nbsp;811-813; 819\n\n* [[Jos\u00e9-Apeles Santolaria de Puey y Cruells|Santolaria de Puey y Cruells, Jos\u00e9-Apeles]] [https://books.google.it/books?id=UT1KDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=it#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Annuario Diocesano 2017. Indicatore ecclesiastico per l'anno 2017. Stato del clero e delle parrocchie''], Arcidiocesi di Ferrara-Comacchio 2016\n* [[Jos\u00e9-Apeles Santolaria de Puey y Cruells|Santolaria de Puey y Cruells, Jos\u00e9-Apeles]] ''Gli affreschi della Sala degli stemmi del Palazzo arcivescovile di Ferrara'', Archivio Storico Ecclesiastico di Ferrara, [[Ferrara]] 2017\n*{{cite book|last1=Ughelli|first1=Ferdinando|last2=Coleti|first2=Niccol\u00f2|title=Italia sacra sive De Episcopis Italiae, et insularum adjacentium|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gVA-AaVyyMwC|year=1717|publisher=apud Sebastianum Coleti|location=Venice|language=Latin|pages=513\u2013565}}\n\n===Bibliography of churches===\n{{further reading cleanup|date=July 2018}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Alberto Guzzon|author2=Paola Poggipollini|title=Chiese e monasteri di Ferrara: devozione, storia, arte di una citt\u00e0 della fede|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c9ZOAAAAYAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Comunicarte|location=Firenze|language=Italian|isbn=978-88-87527-06-3}}\n*{{cite book|author=Dante Balboni|title=Cavalieri ed edifici dell'Ordine di Malta a Ferrara|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7nPaBwAAQBAJ|year=1989|publisher=Lions Club Ferrara|location=Ferrara|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|author=Cesare Barotti|title=Pitture e scolture che si trovano nelle chiese: luoghi pubblici, e sobborghi della citt\u00e0 di Ferrara|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FX9YAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1|year=1770|publisher=Appresso Giuseppe Rinaldi|location=Ferrara|language=Italian}}\n* {{cite book|last=Baruffaldi|first=Gerolamo|title=Dell' Istoria di Ferrara, scritta dal dottore D. Girolamo Baruffaldi,... libri nove, ne' quali ... si narrano le cose avvenute in essa dall' anno 1655 sino al 1700 ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SyAMF51EI8YC|year=1700|publisher=B. Pomatelli|location=Ferrara|language=Italian}}\n* Andrea Borsetti ''Supplemento al Compendio historico del Guarini''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* COMITATO DIOCESANO PER IL GRANDE GIUBILEO 2000 ''Guida del pellegrino in terra ferrarese''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* FERRARIAE DECUS ''Chiese di Ferrara antiche e nuove''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* Giovannini, Claudio (2005). ''Alla ricerca delle 103 chiese, monasteri, oratori esistenti in Ferrara nell'anno 1782'' Ferrara: 2005. {{in lang|it}}\n* {{cite book|author=Marc'Antonio Guarini|title=Compendio historico dell'origine, accrescimento, e prerogatiue delle Chiese, e luoghi pij della citta, e diocesi di Ferrara, e delle memorie di que' personaggi di pregio, che in esse son sepelliti: ... opera non meno curiosa che diletteuole descritta per D. Marc'Antonio Guarini ferrarese, ..|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I4iMLK8jgQoC|year=1621|publisher=presso gli heredi di Vittorio Baldini|location=Ferrara|language=Italian}}\n* {{cite book|last=Libanori|first=Antonio |title=Ferrara d'oro imbrunito|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-liMZ4i2BNgC|volume=Vol. 1|year=1665|publisher=Per Alfonso e Gio. Battista Maresti|location=Ferrara|language=Italian}}\n* [[Ugo Malag\u00f9]] ''Guida del ferrarese''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* Alfonso Maresti ''Teatro genealogico et istorico''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* Gualtiero Medri ''Chiese di Ferrara nella cerchia antica''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* {{cite book|last=Muratori|first=Lodovico Antonio |title=Delle antichit\u00e0 estensi ed italiane trattato di Lodovico Antonio Muratori bibliotecario del serenissimo Rinaldo 1.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8AE18BoSgbsC|volume=Parte prima|year=1717|publisher=nella stamperia ducale|location=Modena|language=Italian}}\n* [[Giuseppe Antenore Scalabrini]] ''Guida per la citt\u00e0 e i borghi di Ferrara in cinque giornate''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* {{cite book|author=Giuseppe Antenore Scalabrini|title=Memorie istoriche delle chiese di Ferrara e de' suoi borghi: Munite, ed illustrate con antichi inediti monumenti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J4BYAAAAcAAJ|year=1773|publisher=per C. Coatti|location=Ferrara|language=Italian}}\n* Marcello Toffanello ''Ferrara Guide''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* TOURING CLUB ''Ferrara e provincia''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* Piero Vigan\u00f2 ''Ferrara, il fascino del suo territorio''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n* Piero Vigan\u00f2 ''Paesi e parrocchie dell\u2019Arcidiocesi di Ferrara''{{Full citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/06046a.htm Source]\n{{Catholic}}\n\n{{coord missing|Italy}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Bologna}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Emilia-Romagna|Ferrara]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Ferrara| ]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 4th century|Ferrara]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Archdiocese_of_Ferrara-Comacchio"}
{"title_page": "Harry Brearley", "text_new": "{{short description|English inventor of stainless steel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n[[File:Harry Brearley.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Monument to Harry Brearley at the former [[Firth Brown Steels|Brown Firth Research Laboratories]] in [[Sheffield]], England]]\n\n'''Harry Brearley''' (18 February 1871 \u2013 14 July 1948)\nwas an English metallurgist, credited with the invention of \"rustless steel\" (later to be called \"[[stainless steel]]\" in the anglophone world). Based in [[Sheffield]], his invention brought affordable [[cutlery]] to the masses, and saw an expansion of the city\u2019s traditional cutlery trade.<ref>{{cite news |title=Made in Great Britain, Series 1, Steel |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0bpz4ks |accessdate=28 March 2019 |agency=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBrearley was born on 18 February 1871 in [[Sheffield]], [[England]], the son of John Brearley, a steelworker, and his wife, Jane Brearley n\u00e9e Senior.<ref name=ODNB>Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, accessed 2 April 2013</ref> He left Woodside school at the age of twelve to enter his first employment as a labourer in his father's steelworks, later getting the post of general assistant in the company's chemical laboratory.  He married Helen Theresa Crank (1874\u20131955) on 23 October 1895.<ref name=ODNB/>\nFor several years, in addition to his laboratory work, he studied at home and later in formal evening classes, to specialize in steel production techniques and associated chemical analysis methods.\n\nBy his early thirties, Brearley had earned a reputation as an experienced professional and for being very astute in the resolution of practical, industrial, metallurgical problems.  It was in 1908, when two of Sheffield's principal [[steelmaking]] companies innovatively agreed to jointly finance a common research laboratory ([[Firth Brown Steels|Brown Firth Laboratories]]) that Harry Brearley was asked to lead the project.\n\nAfter leaving Brown Firth, Brearley joined [[Brown Bayley Steels|Brown Bayley's Steel Works]], also in Sheffield; he became a director of the firm in 1925.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn 1941 Brearley created a charitable trust The Freshgate Trust Foundation, a grantmaking charity operating in Sheffield and South Yorkshire. His aim was to provide a \"Fresh Gate\" or new opportunity to people like him born into modest circumstances so that they may experience the finer things in life such as travel, education, the arts and music. The foundation is still operating as a [[Charitable organization|registered charity]] awarding grants for charitable purposes in South Yorkshire.<ref>{{EW charity|221467|The Freshgate Trust Foundation}}</ref>\n\nBrearley died on 14 July 1948, at [[Torquay]], a [[seaside resort|coastal resort town]] in Devon, south west England. He was cremated at Efford Crematorium, Efford, near [[Plymouth]] on 16 July 1948<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> and his ashes were scattered in the Efford Crematorium Garden of Remembrance.<ref>Confirmed in a letter dated 30 September 1994 from the City of Plymouth Cemeteries Manager to Dr Peter Beeley of Cookridge, Leeds</ref>\n\nIn 2013, in the Sheffield University Varsity Brewing Challenge, Sheffield University named their beer \u2013 brewed by Thornbridge \u2013 Brearleys, to commemorate 100 years since Harry Brearley invented stainless steel.\n\n== Stainless steel==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=August 2015}}\nIn the troubled years immediately before the [[First World War]], arms manufacturing increased significantly in the UK, but practical problems were encountered due to erosion (excessive wear) of the internal surfaces of gun barrels. Brearley began to research new steels which could better resist the erosion caused by high temperatures (rather than corrosion, as is often mentioned in this regard). He began to examine the addition of [[chromium]] to steel, which was known to raise the material's melting point, as compared to the standard [[carbon]] steels.\n\nThe research concentrated on quantifying the effects of varying the levels of [[carbon]] (C, at concentrations around 0.2 weight %) and [[chromium]] (Cr, in the range of 6 to 15 weight %).\n\n===The accidental discovery ===\n[[Image:Stainless steel nyt 1-31-1915.jpg|right|thumb|Announcement of Brearley's stainless steel discovery as it appeared in the 1915 ''[[New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite journal|journal=New York Times|title=A non-rusting steel|date=31 January 1915}}</ref>]]\nIn order to undertake [[metallography]] to study the [[microstructure]] of the experimental alloys (the main factor responsible for a steel's mechanical properties) it was necessary to [[polishing|polish]] and [[Chemical milling|etch]] the metallic samples produced. For a carbon steel, a dilute solution of [[nitric acid]] in [[ethanol|alcohol]] is sufficient to produce the required etching, but Brearley found that the new chromium steels were very resistant to chemical attack.\nhe was poo poo head\n===Development===\nIt was probably Harry Brearley's upbringing in Sheffield, a city famous for the manufacture of [[cutlery]] since the 16th century, which led him to appreciate the potential of these new steels for applications not only in high-temperature service, as originally envisioned, but also in the mass-production of food-related applications such as cutlery, [[saucepan]]s and processing equipment etc. Up to that time carbon-steel knives were prone to unhygienic [[rust]]ing if they were not frequently polished and only expensive [[sterling silver]] or [[nickel silver|EPNS]] cutlery was generally available to avoid such problems. With this in mind Brearley extended his examinations to include tests with food acids such as [[vinegar]] and [[lemon juice]], with very promising results.\n\nBrearley initially called the new alloy \"rustless steel\"; the more [[euphony|euphonic]] \"stainless steel\" was suggested by Ernest Stuart of [[R.F. Mosley's]], a local cutlery manufacturer at [[Portland Works]], and eventually prevailed although Mosley's used the \"Rusnorstain\" trademark for many years. It is reported<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stainlesssteel.or.kr/english/stsinfo/develop.asp |title=The development of stainless steel |publisher=Stainless Steel Club |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050827005100/http://www.stainlesssteel.or.kr/english/stsinfo/develop.asp |archivedate=27 August 2005 |accessdate=22 July 2011}}</ref> that the first true stainless steel, a 0.24wt% C, 12.8wt% Cr ferrous [[alloy]], was produced by Brearley in an electric [[furnace]] on 13 August 1913. He was subsequently awarded the [[Iron and Steel Institute]]'s [[Bessemer Gold Medal]] in 1920.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.tilthammer.com/bio/brear.html Tilt Hammer \u2013 Steel City Founders \u2013 Harry Brearley<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061121041226/http://www.tilthammer.com/bio/brear.html |date=21 November 2006 }}</ref>  The [[ASM International (society)|American Society for Metals]] gives the date for Brearley's creation of casting number 1008 (12.8% chromium, 0.44% manganese, 0.2% silicon, 0.24% carbon and 85.32% iron) as 20 August 1913.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=E30rCBeM8nkC&pg=PA41&dq=Harry+Brearley+August+1913&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Z60wUb-IKJH08ATWz4D4Ag&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Harry%20Brearley%20August%201913&f=false ''The History of Stainless Steel''], by Harold M. Cobb,  (ASM International, 2010) p41</ref>\n\nVirtually all research projects into the further development of stainless steels were interrupted by the 1914\u201318 War, but efforts were renewed in the 1920s. Brearley had left the Brown Firth Laboratories in 1915, following disagreements regarding [[patent]] rights, but the research continued under the direction of his successor, Dr. [[W. H. Hatfield]]. It is Hatfield who is credited with the development, in 1924, of a stainless steel which even today is probably the widest-used alloy of this type, the so-called \"[[18/8 stainless steel|18/8]]\", which in addition to chromium, includes [[nickel]] (Ni) in its composition (18wt% Cr, 8wt% Ni).\n\n== Memorials ==\n\nA {{convert|42|ft|m}} mural of Brearley, marking the 100th anniversary of his invention of stainless steel, was commissioned for the side of a building on Howard Street, Sheffield, and was painted by the artist [[Sarah Yates]] (aka \"Faunagraphic\").<ref name=\"SAS\">{{cite web |title=Harry Brearley |url=http://streetartsheffield.com/gallery/harry-brearley |publisher=Street Art Sheffield |accessdate=30 December 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* H. Brearley & F. Ibbotson (1902) ''The Analysis of Steel-works Materials''\n* H. Brearley (1911) ''The Heat Treatment of Tool Steel''\n* H. Brearley (1914) ''The Case-Hardening of Steel'' \n* H. Brearley (1918) ''The Heat Treatment of Steel''\n* H. Brearley (1933) ''Steel Makers''\n* H. Brearley (1941) ''Knotted String''  (autobiography)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people from Sheffield]]\n*[[Elwood Haynes]]\n*[[Portland Works]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Harry Brearley}}\n<!--*[http://www.stainlesssteel.or.kr/english/stsinfo/develop.asp The development of stainless steel] Dead link -->\n*[http://www.tilthammer.com/bio/brear.html Biography]\n*Archive.org, list of books by creator:[https://archive.org/search.php?query=creator%3A%22Brearley%2C+Harry%2C+b.+1871%22 \"Brearley, Harry, b. 1871]\"\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brearley, Harry}}\n[[Category:British metallurgists]]\n[[Category:English inventors]]\n[[Category:History of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:People from Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Stainless steel]]\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English inventor of stainless steel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n[[File:Harry Brearley.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Monument to Harry Brearley at the former [[Firth Brown Steels|Brown Firth Research Laboratories]] in [[Sheffield]], England]]\n\n'''Harry Brearley''' (18 February 1871 \u2013 14 July 1948)\nwas an English metallurgist, credited with the invention of \"rustless steel\" (later to be called \"[[stainless steel]]\" in the anglophone world). Based in [[Sheffield]], his invention brought affordable [[cutlery]] to the masses, and saw an expansion of the city\u2019s traditional cutlery trade.<ref>{{cite news |title=Made in Great Britain, Series 1, Steel |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0bpz4ks |accessdate=28 March 2019 |agency=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBrearley was born on 18 February 1871 in [[Sheffield]], [[England]], the son of John Brearley, a steelworker, and his wife, Jane Brearley n\u00e9e Senior.<ref name=ODNB>Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, accessed 2 April 2013</ref> He left Woodside school at the age of twelve to enter his first employment as a labourer in his father's steelworks, later getting the post of general assistant in the company's chemical laboratory.  He married Helen Theresa Crank (1874\u20131955) on 23 October 1895.<ref name=ODNB/>\nFor several years, in addition to his laboratory work, he studied at home and later in formal evening classes, to specialize in steel production techniques and associated chemical analysis methods.\n\nBy his early thirties, Brearley had earned a reputation as an experienced professional and for being very astute in the resolution of practical, industrial, metallurgical problems.  It was in 1908, when two of Sheffield's principal [[steelmaking]] companies innovatively agreed to jointly finance a common research laboratory ([[Firth Brown Steels|Brown Firth Laboratories]]) that Harry Brearley was asked to lead the project.\n\nAfter leaving Brown Firth, Brearley joined [[Brown Bayley Steels|Brown Bayley's Steel Works]], also in Sheffield; he became a director of the firm in 1925.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn 1941 Brearley created a charitable trust The Freshgate Trust Foundation, a grantmaking charity operating in Sheffield and South Yorkshire. His aim was to provide a \"Fresh Gate\" or new opportunity to people like him born into modest circumstances so that they may experience the finer things in life such as travel, education, the arts and music. The foundation is still operating as a [[Charitable organization|registered charity]] awarding grants for charitable purposes in South Yorkshire.<ref>{{EW charity|221467|The Freshgate Trust Foundation}}</ref>\n\nBrearley died on 14 July 1948, at [[Torquay]], a [[seaside resort|coastal resort town]] in Devon, south west England. He was cremated at Efford Crematorium, Efford, near [[Plymouth]] on 16 July 1948<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> and his ashes were scattered in the Efford Crematorium Garden of Remembrance.<ref>Confirmed in a letter dated 30 September 1994 from the City of Plymouth Cemeteries Manager to Dr Peter Beeley of Cookridge, Leeds</ref>\n\nIn 2013, in the Sheffield University Varsity Brewing Challenge, Sheffield University named their beer \u2013 brewed by Thornbridge \u2013 Brearleys, to commemorate 100 years since Harry Brearley invented stainless steel.\n\n== Stainless steel==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=August 2015}}\nIn the troubled years immediately before the [[First World War]], arms manufacturing increased significantly in the UK, but practical problems were encountered due to erosion (excessive wear) of the internal surfaces of gun barrels. Brearley began to research new steels which could better resist the erosion caused by high temperatures (rather than corrosion, as is often mentioned in this regard). He began to examine the addition of [[chromium]] to steel, which was known to raise the material's melting point, as compared to the standard [[carbon]] steels.\n\nThe research concentrated on quantifying the effects of varying the levels of [[carbon]] (C, at concentrations around 0.2 weight %) and [[chromium]] (Cr, in the range of 6 to 15 weight %).\n\n===The accidental discovery ===\n[[Image:Stainless steel nyt 1-31-1915.jpg|right|thumb|Announcement of Brearley's stainless steel discovery as it appeared in the 1915 ''[[New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite journal|journal=New York Times|title=A non-rusting steel|date=31 January 1915}}</ref>]]\nIn order to undertake [[metallography]] to study the [[microstructure]] of the experimental alloys (the main factor responsible for a steel's mechanical properties) it was necessary to [[polishing|polish]] and [[Chemical milling|etch]] the metallic samples produced. For a carbon steel, a dilute solution of [[nitric acid]] in [[ethanol|alcohol]] is sufficient to produce the required etching, but Brearley found that the new chromium steels were very resistant to chemical attack.\n\n===Development===\nIt was probably Harry Brearley's upbringing in Sheffield, a city famous for the manufacture of [[cutlery]] since the 16th century, which led him to appreciate the potential of these new steels for applications not only in high-temperature service, as originally envisioned, but also in the mass-production of food-related applications such as cutlery, [[saucepan]]s and processing equipment etc. Up to that time carbon-steel knives were prone to unhygienic [[rust]]ing if they were not frequently polished and only expensive [[sterling silver]] or [[nickel silver|EPNS]] cutlery was generally available to avoid such problems. With this in mind Brearley extended his examinations to include tests with food acids such as [[vinegar]] and [[lemon juice]], with very promising results.\n\nBrearley initially called the new alloy \"rustless steel\"; the more [[euphony|euphonic]] \"stainless steel\" was suggested by Ernest Stuart of [[R.F. Mosley's]], a local cutlery manufacturer at [[Portland Works]], and eventually prevailed although Mosley's used the \"Rusnorstain\" trademark for many years. It is reported<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stainlesssteel.or.kr/english/stsinfo/develop.asp |title=The development of stainless steel |publisher=Stainless Steel Club |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050827005100/http://www.stainlesssteel.or.kr/english/stsinfo/develop.asp |archivedate=27 August 2005 |accessdate=22 July 2011}}</ref> that the first true stainless steel, a 0.24wt% C, 12.8wt% Cr ferrous [[alloy]], was produced by Brearley in an electric [[furnace]] on 13 August 1913. He was subsequently awarded the [[Iron and Steel Institute]]'s [[Bessemer Gold Medal]] in 1920.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.tilthammer.com/bio/brear.html Tilt Hammer \u2013 Steel City Founders \u2013 Harry Brearley<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061121041226/http://www.tilthammer.com/bio/brear.html |date=21 November 2006 }}</ref>  The [[ASM International (society)|American Society for Metals]] gives the date for Brearley's creation of casting number 1008 (12.8% chromium, 0.44% manganese, 0.2% silicon, 0.24% carbon and 85.32% iron) as 20 August 1913.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=E30rCBeM8nkC&pg=PA41&dq=Harry+Brearley+August+1913&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Z60wUb-IKJH08ATWz4D4Ag&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Harry%20Brearley%20August%201913&f=false ''The History of Stainless Steel''], by Harold M. Cobb,  (ASM International, 2010) p41</ref>\n\nVirtually all research projects into the further development of stainless steels were interrupted by the 1914\u201318 War, but efforts were renewed in the 1920s. Brearley had left the Brown Firth Laboratories in 1915, following disagreements regarding [[patent]] rights, but the research continued under the direction of his successor, Dr. [[W. H. Hatfield]]. It is Hatfield who is credited with the development, in 1924, of a stainless steel which even today is probably the widest-used alloy of this type, the so-called \"[[18/8 stainless steel|18/8]]\", which in addition to chromium, includes [[nickel]] (Ni) in its composition (18wt% Cr, 8wt% Ni).\n\n== Memorials ==\n\nA {{convert|42|ft|m}} mural of Brearley, marking the 100th anniversary of his invention of stainless steel, was commissioned for the side of a building on Howard Street, Sheffield, and was painted by the artist [[Sarah Yates]] (aka \"Faunagraphic\").<ref name=\"SAS\">{{cite web |title=Harry Brearley |url=http://streetartsheffield.com/gallery/harry-brearley |publisher=Street Art Sheffield |accessdate=30 December 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* H. Brearley & F. Ibbotson (1902) ''The Analysis of Steel-works Materials''\n* H. Brearley (1911) ''The Heat Treatment of Tool Steel''\n* H. Brearley (1914) ''The Case-Hardening of Steel'' \n* H. Brearley (1918) ''The Heat Treatment of Steel''\n* H. Brearley (1933) ''Steel Makers''\n* H. Brearley (1941) ''Knotted String''  (autobiography)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people from Sheffield]]\n*[[Elwood Haynes]]\n*[[Portland Works]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Harry Brearley}}\n<!--*[http://www.stainlesssteel.or.kr/english/stsinfo/develop.asp The development of stainless steel] Dead link -->\n*[http://www.tilthammer.com/bio/brear.html Biography]\n*Archive.org, list of books by creator:[https://archive.org/search.php?query=creator%3A%22Brearley%2C+Harry%2C+b.+1871%22 \"Brearley, Harry, b. 1871]\"\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brearley, Harry}}\n[[Category:British metallurgists]]\n[[Category:English inventors]]\n[[Category:History of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:People from Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Stainless steel]]\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Yorkshire]]\n", "name_user": "82.47.225.0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eStainless steel)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Brearley"}
{"title_page": "Nova Scotia Highway 103", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|province=NS\n|type=Hwy\n|route=103\n|alternate_name=Fishermen's Memorial Highway\n|maint=[[Nova Scotia Department of Transportation and Infrastructure Renewal]]\n|map=Nova Scotia 103-Map.png\n|length_km=291.3\n|length_round=1\n|length_ref=<ref name=length>{{google maps|title=Highway 103 in Nova Scotia|url=https://goo.gl/maps/iNi8JFL4Amo9qr3W7|accessdate=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|established=1949\n|direction_a=East\n|direction_b=West\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=NS|Hwy|102}} in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]]\n|junction={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|14}} near [[Chester, Nova Scotia|Chester]]<br />{{jct|state=NS|Trunk|10}} near [[Bridgewater, Nova Scotia|Bridgewater]]<br />{{jct|state=NS|Trunk|8}} near [[Liverpool, Nova Scotia|Liverpool]]\n|terminus_b=Hardscratch Road in [[Yarmouth, NS|Yarmouth]]\n|counties=[[Halifax Regional Municipality]], [[Lunenburg County, Nova Scotia|Lunenburg]], [[Queens County, Nova Scotia|Queens]], [[Shelburne County, Nova Scotia|Shelburne]], [[Yarmouth County, Nova Scotia|Yarmouth]]\n|previous_type=Hwy\n|previous_route=102\n|next_type=TCH\n|next_route=104\n}}\n\n'''Highway 103''' is an east-west highway in [[Nova Scotia]] that runs from [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] to [[Yarmouth, Nova Scotia|Yarmouth]].\n\nThe highway follows a route of {{convert|291|km|mi}} along the province's [[South Shore (Nova Scotia)|South Shore]] region fronting the Atlantic coast. The route parallels its predecessor, local [[Nova Scotia Trunk 3|Trunk&nbsp;3]]. The highway varies from 2-lane controlled access to 2-lane local secondary roads on the section between Yarmouth and [[Hebbville, Nova Scotia|Hebbville]]. East of Hebbville to [[Upper Tantallon, Nova Scotia|Upper Tantallon]], the highway is 2-lane controlled access, with the exception of a {{convert|3|km|mi|abbr=on|0}} 4-lane [[divided highway|divided freeway]] near [[Chester Basin, Nova Scotia|Chester]]. From Upper Tantallon (Exit 5), to the interchange with [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway&nbsp;102]] (near Bayers Lake) in Halifax, the highway is 4-lane divided freeway. Similar to [[Nova Scotia Highway 101|Highway&nbsp;101]], kilometer markers increase run west-to-east, increasing from Yarmouth to Halifax; however, exit numbers run east-to-west, increasing from Halifax to Yarmouth.\n\nIn 2013, Highway 103 was redesignated as the '''Fishermen's Memorial Highway'''.\n\n==History==\nThe highway has developed sporadically since the 1970s, with the 2-lane controlled access portion to Bridgewater being largely responsible for the abandonment of [[Canadian National Railway|CN Rail]]'s South Shore line, the former [[Halifax and Southwestern Railway]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} In November 2006, construction was completed that twinned 15 kilometers of highway between Exit 3 and Exit 5.<ref>[https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20061211005 Highway 103 Greatly Improved]</ref> In December 2006, an 8.3 kilometre bypass around [[Barrington, Nova Scotia (community)|Barrington]] was completed.<ref>[https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20061221008 Barrington Bypass Completed] Government of Nova Scotia</ref>\n\nIn late September 2015 a new section of highway was opened to bypass the Port Joli area.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Verge|first1=Brittany W.|title=Smoothing out Highway 103: Port Joli bypass opens to traffic|url=http://www.theadvance.ca/news/local/2015/10/12/port-joli-bypass-opens-to-traffic.html|accessdate=30 May 2017|work=Queens County Advance|publisher=Transcontinental Media|date=October 14, 2015}}</ref> In November 2016, a new section was completed which bypassed Port Mouton. Residents complained that the single exit east of the community had lengthened the trip for people heading west from Port Mouton.\n\nThe new interchange in Ingramport (Exit 5A) opened in January 2017.\n\nWork on twinning Highway 103 from Exit 5 (Tantallon) to Exit 5A (Ingramport) began in February, 2018. Construction is expected to be completed by Fall 2020. Twinning from Exit 5A (Ingramport) to Exit 6 (Hubbards) will start in 2020 with an expected completion date of 2023.\n\n==Names of Highway 103==\n\n* Fishermen's Memorial Highway - June 2013\n* Barrington Bypass - [[Barrington, Nova Scotia (community)|Barrington]] to [[Oak Park, Nova Scotia|Oak Park]], [[Shelburne County, Nova Scotia|Shelburne County]] \n* Nine Mile Road - [[Sable River, Nova Scotia|Sable River]] to [[Jordan Falls, Nova Scotia|Jordan Falls]], [[Shelburne County, Nova Scotia|Shelburne County]]\n\n==Safety concerns==\nBetween 2006 and 2009, there were 29 deaths on the highway.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/canada-s-most-notorious-highways-1.1321147 Canada's most notorious highways] CBC.ca</ref> In 2009, it was considered Nova Scotia's deadliest highway and was ranked the second most dangerous highway in Canada by the [[Canadian Automobile Association]].<ref name=\"cbcnews\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-s-highway-101-to-be-widened-1.807138|title=Nova Scotia's Highway 101 to be widened|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=2017-06-26 | date=March 6, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://caaneo.ca/about/blog/driving/the-top-12-most-dangerous-highways-in-canada |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428001133/http://caaneo.ca/about/blog/driving/the-top-12-most-dangerous-highways-in-canada |archivedate=2012-04-28 }} \"The Top 12 Most Dangerous Highways in Canada\"</ref> In 2009 alone, ten people died in automobile accidents on the highway, according to the [[Nova Scotia Department of Transportation and Infrastructure Renewal]].<ref>[http://autos.ca.msn.com/specials/road-trip-guide/gallery.aspx?cp-documentid=25920211&page=9 10 most dangerous roads in Canada] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021045326/http://autos.ca.msn.com/specials/road-trip-guide/gallery.aspx?cp-documentid=25920211&page=9 |date=2010-10-21 }} MSN.ca</ref> Between 2008 and 2012, there were 22 fatalities on the highway.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/highway-103-safety-review-launched-in-nova-scotia-1.2816113 Highway 103 safety review launched in Nova Scotia] CBC.ca</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, local residents raised concern over the presence of a road sign on the highway, near the turnoff to [[Port Mouton]], that had a very confusing appearance, looking like a patchwork of several other road signs. It was supposedly revealed when a hotel removed its billboard advertisement, revealing the sign below.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45478932|title=Is this road sign in Canada the world's most confusing?|publisher=BBC|date=11 September 2018|access-date=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Exit list ==\n{{NSinttop|exit|length_ref=<ref name=length/>}}\n{{Jctint|exit\n|county_special=[[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]]\n|cspan=7\n|location_special=[[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]]\n|lspan=3\n|km=0.0\n|exit=1B\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Hwy|102|Hwy|101|to2=yes|city1=Halifax|city2=Dartmouth|city3=Windsor|location4=[[Halifax International Airport|Airport]]|city5=Truro|city6=Bedford|extra=airport}}\n|notes=Hwy&nbsp;103 eastern terminus.\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|km=0.4\n|type=incomplete\n|exit=1D\n|road=[[Dunbrack Street]]\n|notes=Eastbound exit only.\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|km=1.2\n|exit=2\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|3|name1=St. Margarets Bay Road|to2=yes|Route|333|dir1=west|name2=[[Lighthouse Route]]|city1=Beechville|city2=Lakeside|city3=Peggys Cove}}\n|notes=Westbound signed as exits 2A (west) and 2B (east)\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Timberlea\n|exit=3\n|km=5.6\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|3|to1=yes|road=Timberlea Village Parkway}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Hubley\n|exit=4\n|km=12.7\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|3|city1=Timberlea|city2=Five Island Lake}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Upper Tantallon\n|exit=5\n|km=19.6\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Route|213|name1=Hammond's Plains Road|to2=yes|Trunk|3|Route|333|city1=Peggys Cove|city2=Bedford}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=none\n|exit=5A\n|km=29.9\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|3|to1=yes|city1=Ingramport|city2=Black Point|city3=Boutiliers Point}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|county=Lunenburg\n|cspan=12\n|location=Hubbards\n|exit=6\n|km=40.8\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|3|Route|329|city1=Queensland|city2=Blandford}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=East River\n|exit=7\n|km=50.0\n|type=\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|3|Route|329|city1=Chester|city2=Blandford}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Chester\n|exit=8\n|km=57.2\n|type=\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|14|city1=Chester|city2=Windsor}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Chester Basin\n|exit=9\n|km=61.3\n|type=\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|12|city1=Kentville|city2=New Ross}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Mahone Bay\n|exit=10\n|km=75.0\n|type=\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|3|city1=Lunenburg|city2=Martin's River}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Blockhouse\n|exit=11\n|km=79.9\n|type=\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Route|324|name1=Cornwall Road|Route|325|to2=yes|city1=Mahone Bay|city2=Lunenburg}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Bridgewater\n|lspan=3\n|exit=12\n|km=91.6\n|type=\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|10|to2=yes|Route|331|Route|332|city1=West LaHave|city2=East LaHave|city3=Riverport}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{Jctplace|exit\n|km=91.8\n|place=Crosses the [[LaHave River]]\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|km=94.8\n|exit=13\n|type=\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Route|325|name1=Victoria Road|to2=yes|Route|331|city1=Bakers Settlement|city2=Wileville}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Hebb's Cross\n|exit=14\n|km=101.4\n|type=\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Trunk|3|dir1=east|city1=Hebbville|city2=Bridgewater}}\n|notes=At-grade\n}}\n{{NSint|exit\n|location=Italy Cross\n|exit=15\n|km=107.9\n|type=\n|road=Italy Cross Road&nbsp;\u2212 [[Crousetown, Nova Scotia|Crousetown]], [[Petite Riviere, Nova Scotia|Petite Riviere]], [[Broad Cove, Nova Scotia|Broad Cove]], Ris